To create a login page in Figma, a number of steps are required as this involves creating multiple components such as frames, rectangles, and texts for the structure and content. Below is a code snippet on how to create a simple login page.

```tsx
async function createLoginPage() {
  // Create container frame
  const container = await assistant.functions.create_frame({
    x: 0,
    y: 0,
    width: 800,
    height: 600,
    name: "login_page",
    fillColor: { r: 1, g: 1, b: 1, a: 1 }
  });

  const containerId = container.nodes[0];

  // Create username input
  const usernameInput = await assistant.functions.create_rectangle({
    x: 100,
    y: 50,
    width: 180,
    height: 120,
    name: "username_input",
    parentId: containerId
  });

  // Create password input
  const passwordInput = await assistant.functions.create_rectangle({
    x: 100,
    y: 180,
    width: 180,
    height: 120,
    name: "password_input",
    parentId: containerId
  });

  // Create login button
  const loginButton = await assistant.functions.create_rectangle({
    x: 100,
    y: 310,
    width: 180,
    height: 120,
    name: "login_button",
    parentId: containerId
  });

  // Set texts
  await assistant.functions.create_text({
    x: 110,
    y: 75,
    text: "Username",
    fontSize: 18,
    parentId: containerId
  });

  await assistant.functions.create_text({
    x: 110,
    y: 205,
    text: "Password",
    fontSize: 18,
    parentId: containerId
  });

  await assistant.functions.create_text({
    x: 110,
    y: 335,
    text: "Login",
    fontSize: 18,
    parentId: containerId
  });
}

createLoginPage();
```

This script creates a frame as a container for the page, then creates a username input, password input, and a login button. Note that this just creates the structure for the login page, additional styling might be required.
